main event: A bright, star-like object was observed moving in a straight pattern from southwest to northeast over Philadelphia, Pennsylvania in August 1956.
interesting points: The object was described as a bright, whitish, and traveling at high speed, consistent with a satellite.
The observer initially thought it was a star, but then realized it was moving.
The object later seemed to split into two objects that moved in an erratic manner, zig-zagging and hovering.
The objects were estimated to be around 1000 feet in altitude and were visible for about 10 minutes.
The observer was a pilot trained in aircraft identification and had no explanation for what was observed.
sighted object: a bright, whitish, star-like object that split into two erratically moving objects
witnesses: a civilian observer, possibly a pilot
photographs: no photographs, only a typed record
